dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Pilkington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (northwestern): habitational name from a place in Lancashire. The placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Pīleca</i> or <i>Pīloc</i> + patronymic <i>-ing</i> + Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. The surname is established in Ireland, where its presence was first recorded in the early 15th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Pilkerton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]},{"name":"Pilkinton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]},{"name":"Pilkenton","meanings":["English: variant of   Pilkington  ."]}]},{"name":"Leonard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name of Germanic origin, derived from <i>leon</i> ‘lion’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. This was the name of a 5th-century Frankish saint, the patron of peasants and horses. Although it was introduced into Britain by the Normans, <i>Leonard</i> was an uncommon name during the Middle Ages. It was revived in some areas towards the end of the 1400s, and in the 19th‐century became very popular. It is now also common as a Jewish name (  compare  Leon  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Lennard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Leonard  , in part a transferred use of the surname, which was derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Leonard de Pilkington I was born in 1050, in Bury, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. He had at least 1 son. He died after 1066, in Pilkington, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1050–after 1066":"1050–pärast 1066","1085–1110":"1085–1110","1050–1066":"1050–1066","1066":"1066","1110":"1110","after 1066":"pärast 1066","1085":"1085","1050":"1050","Bury, Lancashire, England":"Bury, Lancashire, Inglismaa,